    "content": "A group of parliamentarians from the House of the People and the Upper House of Somalia's Federal Parliament has leveled accusations against the Somali National Army (SNA) over a recent clash in the Laag area of Bari region, located in the semi-autonomous state of Puntland. The lawmakers allege that federal troops initiated the confrontation, which resulted in casualties, though specific numbers have not been confirmed.\n\nThe incident occurred amid ongoing tensions between Mogadishu and Puntland, which have been at odds over issues of resource sharing, security arrangements, and political representation. Puntland has long maintained its own security forces and has resisted what it sees as federal overreach. The clash in Laag is the latest in a series of disputes that have occasionally turned violent.\n\nThe accused SNA unit is part of forces deployed to combat al-Shabaab militants in central and southern Somalia, but operations in Puntland have been a source of friction. Local officials in Puntland have previously criticized federal military movements without prior coordination.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this incident underscores the fragile state of federal-state relations in Somalia. The diaspora community, which often follows political developments closely, may view this as a sign of instability that could affect remittances, investment, and the overall security of family members back home. It also raises concerns about the effectiveness of joint counterterrorism efforts.\n\nThe case has sparked calls for an investigation from some MPs, who urge dialogue to resolve grievances. However, no official response from the federal government or the Ministry of Defense has been released at the time of reporting.\n\nRead the original report from Horseed Media here: https://horseedmedia.net/xildhibaano-dfs-ku-eedeeyey-dagaalkii-ka-dhacay-deegaanka-laag-ee-gobolka-bari/423984/",
